title: For Sale:  AK74 - CUR2 Dragunov Style with Real PSO-1 Sniper Scope
postcontent:
This is a rare CUR2 AK74 that was made in Romania and equipped with the Dragunov style furniture. Rifle fires the 5.45 x 39 round which is inherently more accurate than the 7.62 x 39 cartridge. It has been fired very little and is in excellent condition with a mirror bright bore. 

The CUR2 model is the first AK74 style rifle ever imported to the USA and is said to be the best AK rifle of any kind that ever came from Romania right up to present day. It's also quite hard to find because the CUR2 was only imported for one year - 1997.

The stock and hand guard appears to be made of laminated wood and they have a shiny varnish type finish much like the old style Russian AK furniture but without the reddish tint/color. This one is more of a light blond color. Metal finish looks to be a black phosphor. 

I outfitted this rifle with a real PSO-1 scope that was made in Belarus in the 1970's. The PSO-1 was said to be the most advanced military scope of it's time and it was originally designed specifically for the Dragunov sniper rifle. The scope has a magnesium body and is 6x magnification with a 24mm objective lens. It also has an red illuminated reticle, however the special sized Russian battery that came with it expired years ago. I'm told that there is an inexpensive adapter for the PSO scope available on line today that allows the use of readily available American made lithium batteries. The scope is fully functional without the illumination feature which is typically only used in very low light conditions. 

Scope is in excellent shape too and has a silver/gray hammered metal finish. It comes with an original soft rubber eyepiece, a tool to change the illumination diode, khaki green canvas cover, and a winter battery adapter. The PSO-1 scope commands a higher price than the later POSP models and they sell for $300+ no matter where you look.  

Additionally the rifle comes with an original AK74 style web sling, three TAPCO 30 round black polymer mags, and two original military Orange Bakelite 30 round mags. These Bakelite mags are E.German and are very desirable today selling for $50 on up apiece. 

Finally 400 rounds of Romanian 5.45 x 39 MATCH ammo is included - (17) unopened 20 round boxes, and 30 rounds loaded into each Bakelite mag. 

Asking price for everything is $1100 with pickup in the Brandon area. Buyer must be a Florida resident who is at least 21 years old. 

ps: going through a box of gun stuff I found 2 additional brand new Tapco 30 round
mags and they will be included with the rifle. So total mags are 7 - 2 German Bakelite &
5 Tapco black polymer.

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Rasheed Semi-Auto Carbine - 7.62 x 39
postcontent:
For sale is a Rasheed carbine that was made in Egypt just as the AK47 was gaining in popularity. There were only 8000 ever made making them one of the more rare production rifles ever made. My research indicates that only about 2000 were ever imported into the USA. 

This is one the nicest example I've seen in 37 years of collecting military firearms. Most of these are pretty rough because of the service they saw in harsh conditions.This one rates an honest very good to excellent in all respects - metal finish, wood, bore and mechanical function. 

It fires the same standard 7.62 x 39 cartridge that the SKS & AK47 does. It's designed to be top loaded with stripper clips just like the SKS. There are after market detachable mags made that offer higher capacity, and I see them on GunBroker from time to time. 

Rifle comes with it's original issue sling. 

I'm asking $900

title: For Sale:  .58 Caliber 1864 Springfield Civil War Muzzle Loader Rifle
postcontent: I have an original 1864 stamped Springfield .58 muzzle loader civil war rifle for sale. Marked with "S.N. & W.T.C. FOR MASSACHUSETTS" on the lock plate, S. Norris and W.T. Clement of Springfield, Mass. produced approximately 11,000 of these on direct contract for the State of Massachusetts in 1863-1864. The rifle is completely intact with all original parts and is in really good shape. This is the 3-band, 40" barrel version.  All cartouches and marks are still clearly visible - even on the stock.  I took a chance on figuring that the rifle could still be fired and dipped it to clean off the rust so it could be fired.  It has not been cleaned with a wire brush, you will not find any evidence of that.  In fact, I recently had a gunsmith in Bend, OR inspect the barrel and verify that it can be fired using correct procedures and black powder for this weapon.  For those of you who are familiar with the correct procedures, if you wanted to purchase this rifle, I would definitely allow you to fire it before purchasing it - with me present of course. There are some scuffs/scratches on the barrel where the bayonette had been fitted in the past, but I do not have the bayonette. Everything works properly - even the sights fold up and down as they should.  This is a great looking, functional piece of history.  I'm asking $1500, or reasonable offers.
